e and complete inability to heal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStage III intrinsic cuff pathology refers to a \u003Cstrong\u003Etear and tendon failure\u003C/strong\u003E of the rotator cuff. This stage is characterised by a complete tear of the rotator cuff tendon, leading to significant weakness and functional impairment, as seen in this patient who struggles with overhead activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWear and degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E typically describe earlier stages of rotator cuff pathology, where there is fraying and thinning of the tendon without a full-thickness tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepair and vascular response\u003C/strong\u003E would be expected in the healing phase following an injury or surgical intervention, not in the context of a complete tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakage and complete inability to heal\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard description used in the staging of rotator cuff pathology. It implies a chronic, irreparable condition, which is not necessarily the case in stage III pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammation and partial thickness tear\u003C/strong\u003E are features of earlier stages of rotator cuff disease, where there is inflammation and a partial tear, but not a full-thickness tear as seen in stage III.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stage III intrinsic cuff pathology indicates a complete tear of the rotator cuff with tendon failure.","Understanding the stages of rotator cuff pathology is crucial for determining appropriate management strategies."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59156"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59156"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T01:21:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T11:21:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10873"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73683"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{